🧠 The Right Way to “Eat Everything”

(Pantheon Assimilation Protocol v1.0)

0. Gate first (before you touch anything)

Every system must pass 3 checks:

VALUE: does it add a new capability or just duplicate?
COMPATIBILITY: can it map into Pantheon IR?
COST: does it increase complexity more than it adds power?

If it fails → discard early (don’t even ingest)

⸻

1. Strip it to the bone (Pattern Prime extraction)

For each target:

tool → remove branding → remove UI → remove hype → extract invariant

Example:
	•	Git → “versioned state + branching + diff”
	•	Kubernetes → “desired state vs actual state + reconciliation loop”
	•	GraphQL → “structured selective query”

👉 This is your:

Pattern Prime Doctrine in action

⸻

2. Convert to Pantheon IR

Everything must become:
	•	objects
	•	relations
	•	constraints
	•	invariants

If it can’t:

it doesn’t belong in the system

⸻

3. Run Core Passes (this is the “chewing”)

🕷 Spider
	•	map how it connects to existing modules

🪞 Mirror
	•	check contradictions with existing doctrines

🐕 Hound
	•	detect:
	•	overcomplexity
	•	hidden assumptions
	•	redundant patterns

🐦 Raven
	•	compress into:
	•	minimal reusable unit

⸻

4. Integration Test (THIS is where most people fail)

Ask:

Does this:
- improve speed?
- improve clarity?
- improve outcomes?

If not:

spit it out

No sentiment. No attachment.

⸻

5. Attach to Execution (Garcia requirement)

Nothing stays abstract.

Every pattern must connect to:
	•	a workflow
	•	a decision
	•	a measurable output

If it doesn’t:

it’s dead weight

